adaptations. \u003Cstrong\u003EResting heart rate\u003C/strong\u003E typically decreases as an adaptation to regular endurance training. This is due to increased cardiac efficiency and stroke volume, meaning the heart can pump the same amount of blood with fewer beats per minute at rest.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther adaptions that occur include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOxidative enzyme activity\u003C/strong\u003E increases, enhancing the muscle\u0027s ability to produce energy through aerobic pathways, which is crucial for endurance activities.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIncreased numbers and \u003Cstrong\u003Esize of mitochondria\u003C/strong\u003E, allowing for greater aerobic energy production.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMuscle capillary density\u003C/strong\u003E increases, which improves the delivery of oxygen and nutrients to muscle tissues and the removal of metabolic waste products. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECardiac output\u003C/strong\u003E increases due to improved stroke volume and heart rate efficiency, allowing for better oxygen delivery to muscles during exercise.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Resting heart rate decreases with regular exercise due to improved cardiac efficiency.","Exercise adaptation leads to increased mitochondrial size and number, enhancing aerobic capacity.","Cardiac output increases with exercise adaptation due to improved stroke volume and heart rate efficiency.","Muscle capillary density increases with exercise, improving oxygen delivery and waste removal."],"references":["Moghetti P, Bacchi E, Brangani C, Don\u00e0 S, Negri C. Metabolic Effects of Exercise. Front Horm Res. 2016;47:44-57. doi: 10.1159/000445156. Epub 2016 Jun 27. PMID: 27348753.","Thyfault JP, Bergouignan A. Exercise and metabolic health: beyond skeletal muscle. Diabetologia. 2020 Aug;63(8):1464-1474. doi: 10.1007/s00125-020-05177-6. Epub 2020 Jun 11. PMID: 32529412; PMCID: PMC7377236.","Keller J, Zackowski K, Kim S, Chidobem I, Smith M, Farhadi F, Bhargava P. Exercise leads to metabolic changes associated with improved strength and fatigue in people with MS. Ann Clin Transl Neurol. 2021 Jun;8(6):1308-1317. doi: 10.1002/acn3.51368. Epub 2021 May 6. PMID: 33955210; PMCID: PMC8164856.","Gilbert-Barness, E., Barness, L. A., \u0026 Farrell, P. M. (Eds.). (2017). Metabolic diseases: foundations of clinical management, genetics, and pathology. IOS Press","Lanham-New, S. A., Macdonald, I. A., \u0026 Roche, H. M. (Eds.). (2011). Nutrition and metabolism. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Roche, H. M., Macdonald, I. A., Schols, A. M., \u0026 Lanham-New, S. A. (Eds.). (2024). Nutrition and metabolism. John Wiley \u0026 Sons"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94970"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17991"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94970","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94970"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-08T14:03:21+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-08T14:04:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10705"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112938"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"created